<li id="cite_note-50"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-50">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFPaul_Finkelman1989" class="citation book cs1">Paul Finkelman (1989). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=eiMaAQAAIAAJ"><i>Religion and Slavery</i></a>. Garland Pub. p.&#160;397. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780824067960" title="Special:BookSources/9780824067960"><bdi>9780824067960</bdi></a>. <q>If Utah was admitted into the Union as a sovereign State, and we chose to introduce slavery here, it is not their business to meddle, with it; and even if we treated our slaves in an oppressive manner, it is still none of their business and they ought not to meddle with it.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Religion+and+Slavery&amp;rft.pages=397&amp;rft.pub=Garland+Pub.&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.isbn=9780824067960&amp;rft.au=Paul+Finkelman&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DeiMaAQAAIAAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMormonism+and+slavery" class="Z3988"></span></span>
